        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                    <p><img src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.19.20.png" class="type:primaryImage" alt="" /></p>
                
  <p>
    So yesterday, Nintendo released a 2:22 trailer on YouTube for the Nintendo Switch 2, with more information coming on 2/4/2024 (that’s a lot of 2s to be just a coincidence!).
  </p>

  <p>
    The trailer only really shows off what the hardware looks like and has no info about games, specs/power of the system, or release dates outside of its launching in 2025, which we already knew. But some interesting things were confirmed:<br><br><strong>1. The Switch 2 is bigger</strong><br>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52.png" height="2160" width="3840" alt=""  sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-xs.png 300w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-sm.png 480w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-md.png 768w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-lg.png 1024w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-xl.png 1360w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.18.52-2xl.png 1600w">
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    It looks like it has an 8-inch screen and thus bigger Joy-Cons as well. I’ll still be putting something like a grip case on it (so comfortable; if you have not tried one yet, do it! It’s a night and day improvement for ergonomics in handheld mode), but a bigger size overall should be more comfortable for me!<br><br><strong>2. It has a take on the better hinge of the OLED Switch.</strong>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4.png" height="2160" width="3840" alt=""  sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-xs.png 300w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-sm.png 480w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-md.png 768w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-lg.png 1024w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-xl.png 1360w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.21.11-4-2xl.png 1600w">
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    The hinge is the full length of the body, like on the OLED, but thinner. I do wonder how durable this is compared to the OLED, but it should be more stable than the hinge on the original Switch.<br><br><strong>3. It has a USB-C port on the top.</strong>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53.png" height="2160" width="3840" alt=""  sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-xs.png 300w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-sm.png 480w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-md.png 768w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-lg.png 1024w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-xl.png 1360w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.53-2xl.png 1600w">
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    It’s next to the headphone jack and the game card slot, should be handy assuming that you can charge from it/use USB-C headphones from it. Could be used for some other accessories Nintendo might have planned as well. There is still a USB-C port on the bottom of the console like the original Switch.
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20.png" height="2160" width="3840" alt=""  sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-xs.png 300w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-sm.png 480w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-md.png 768w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-lg.png 1024w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-xl.png 1360w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.20-2xl.png 1600w">
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    <strong>4. It’s backwards compatible with original Switch games, both physical game cards and eShop downloads.</strong>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3.png" height="2160" width="3840" alt=""  sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-xs.png 300w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-sm.png 480w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-md.png 768w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-lg.png 1024w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-xl.png 1360w ,https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/responsive/Screenshot-2025-01-17-at-18.20.02-3-2xl.png 1600w">
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    Nintendo does say that it’s not 100% compatible, but if I had to have a guess, these are going to be extreme edge cases, things like the Labo cardboard toys that need you to slot the switch into (hard to do with a physically bigger switch!). <br><br>Another possibility is games that use the IR camera on the bottom of the right Joy-Con; it does not look like it’s there on the new Joy-Cons so far, but a workaround for that could be just using original Joy-Cons for those games connected via Bluetooth, but no details yet.<br><br><strong>5. The Joy-Cons are magnetic.</strong>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/MagneticJoy-Cons-ezgif.com-optimize-2.gif" height="450" width="800" alt="" >
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    &nbsp;Although it looks smart, and I bet the feel of them clicking into place is satisfying, I do wonder how durable they will be.<br><br><strong>6. The Joy-Cons have an optical sensor on them.</strong>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--wide">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://itchster.github.io/media/posts/6/ezgif-3-a997075750.gif" height="450" width="800" alt="" >
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    Nintendo only briefly showed this sensor off (blink and you miss it), but it’s clearly there, opening up the possibility of using either or both Joy-Cons like a mouse. <br><br>So that’s the basics.
  </p>
